title: Blasting the old court house cupola, January 14, 1931
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Seattle, Wash.Three remarkable pictures taken here recently which when perused from left to right form a spectacular movette depicting the removal by blasting of one of Seattle's oldest landmarks, the cupola of the old court house. At the left the ancient structure is shown standing, a second before the wrecker touched off the charge. In the center the entire building is shown a fraction of a second after the 200 sticks of dynamite had been exploded. The pillars atop the cupola are shown flying outward as the understructure is crumbling to ruin. At the right the whole mass of masonry is shown falling in a cloud of dust. Two photographers set their camera in such a way as to catch the three bits of action. Each of the men used two cameras to create the above effect. Great care was exercised to set the charge in such a manner that all debris would fall within the four walls. This was accomplished by placing the dynamite in 36 holes bored in the pillars, between the basement and the first floor. R-1-1-31 ABE.FM"

title: First Presbyterian Church at 3rd Ave. and Madison St., 1889
description: Transcribed from photograph: "This photograph shows left to right: First Presbyterian Church, Third and Madison, Residence of Amos Miller, Residence of M.B.V. Stacey, First Methodist [Episcopal] Church, Third and Marion. The First Presbyterian Church, pictured here, was the first structure erected for the congregation, built in 1877, with the first services in the building held on the first Sunday of July of that year; Rev. Theodore Crown then minister. Church Moved in 1893 to 4th and Spring, and again in 1907 to the present site at Seventh and Spring. Amos Miller site now part of a combined business structure. Stacey home now stands on top of a one story brick block, being used for a French restaurant. This First Methodist Church building erected in 1887, was an outgrowth of the city's first church, known as the "Little White Church" built at 2nd and Columbia, in the early 50's. The property at Third and Marion was sold in 1907 and the congregation established-in a new church at 5th and Marion still in use."
